WEBVTT

00:09.020 --> 00:13.060
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:29.240 --> 00:34.780
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.480 --> 00:39.280
And here are your hosts.

00:44.700 --> 00:46.860
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews.

00:47.180 --> 00:51.400
Some of the most exciting science fiction being written today comes from the pen of Jack Chalker.

00:51.580 --> 00:57.180
And it's clear that he's a popular writer, too, probably best known for the five books in the Well World series.

00:57.480 --> 01:02.300
In fact, the first novel in that series, Midnight at the Well of Souls, has sold over a million copies.

01:02.940 --> 01:08.340
Chalker's first book came out not that long ago, 1976, so his work is still fairly recent.

01:08.340 --> 01:21.840
He'd been active in the field, though, years before he started writing, corresponding with authors and other fans, attending conventions, editing a fanzine, even starting a small publishing company, Mirage Press, to produce material on science fiction.

01:22.040 --> 01:24.820
But Chalker says he'd always planned on being a writer.

01:26.200 --> 01:28.300
I'd always known I was going to be a writer.

01:28.680 --> 01:30.740
I mean, there just was never any question in my mind.

01:31.280 --> 01:34.420
But it was just sort of something that you never really sat down and did.

01:34.580 --> 01:36.920
I used to play around with stories here and there.

01:38.240 --> 01:39.880
John Campbell was a big help.

01:41.880 --> 01:49.700
During the 60s, I would float ideas and fragments off him and he would be very, very nice and tell me exactly what was wrong.

01:49.960 --> 02:01.480
Of course, what infuriated everybody about John Campbell was that the man had been editing for 40 years and he could put his finger on something and tell you exactly what you were doing wrong.

02:01.480 --> 02:06.340
And it was terribly infuriating to discover that he was right in almost every case.

02:07.500 --> 02:10.740
You saw why he did it from 39 until he died.

02:12.580 --> 02:24.000
And as a result of being able to have the help of people like Campbell and August Derleth and a lot of really established writers and editors in the field,

02:25.000 --> 02:30.400
I was able to get a good recognition of exactly what was required in the field.

02:31.520 --> 02:34.220
It just was a matter of sitting down and doing it.

02:35.200 --> 02:39.720
And fortunately, he did sit down and do it, publishing Jungle of Stars in 1976.

02:41.500 --> 02:50.220
So I sat at the typewriter and there was really no question in my mind as to what I'd do first.

02:51.900 --> 02:55.860
I had been playing around with an idea for years and years and years.

02:56.660 --> 03:04.280
There's even a short fanzine version of it, 20 years old, called Jungle or Jungle of Stars.

03:05.320 --> 03:08.400
There were a lot of code words, but jungle was always in it.

03:09.600 --> 03:13.320
And I sat down and wrote the thing.

03:13.620 --> 03:14.180
I wrote it.

03:14.800 --> 03:22.480
It had been around so long in my mind and in discussions and so on that there were just no problems, no resistance,

03:22.880 --> 03:25.260
no having to think it out or anything else.

03:26.260 --> 03:29.420
And I wrote it solidly in about two and a half, three weeks.

03:31.260 --> 03:32.880
And then sent it off.

03:34.680 --> 03:38.380
And it's a good old-fashioned type.

03:39.180 --> 03:42.340
It's a science fiction murder mystery.

03:44.100 --> 03:51.960
Very much at home in the old Astounding, Analogs, and so on, even though it does have some modern touches to it.

03:57.840 --> 04:01.800
Some of his earlier contacts with people in the field of science fiction paid off.

04:02.140 --> 04:04.340
One of them, Judy-Lynn Del Rey, bought the novel.

04:05.680 --> 04:16.260
Judy-Lynn Del Rey, who had just become editor of Ballantine, which was soon to have a science fiction line named after her,

04:18.560 --> 04:19.840
took a look at it.

04:20.060 --> 04:22.400
We'd known each other for about 15 years.

04:23.720 --> 04:30.580
And she put off reading it for quite a long time because she was afraid that if it was terrible and she said so,

04:30.700 --> 04:33.220
that, you know, she'd blow our friendship or something.

04:33.920 --> 04:39.960
Finally, she said, we got together at a convention and she admitted to me all this.

04:40.080 --> 04:41.900
She said, okay, I'll read it, but be prepared.

04:42.440 --> 04:46.580
And about four days later, I get a phone call and she said, hey, this is great.

04:46.600 --> 04:47.400
I want to buy it.

04:48.760 --> 04:50.420
And that was the first sale.

04:52.060 --> 04:56.000
Since then, Chalker has published some 13 novels and he's still going strong.

04:56.380 --> 04:58.260
More with Jack Chalker next time.

