This is the Science Fiction Radio Show,

06:21.140 --> 06:23.700
a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:26.400 --> 06:28.120
And here are your hosts.

06:33.120 --> 06:34.460
This is David Crews.

06:34.680 --> 06:35.360
And Daryl Lane.

06:35.640 --> 06:39.060
A hike through a national park and a war game board,

06:39.320 --> 06:42.640
unlikely sources for a tremendously popular science fiction novel.

06:42.860 --> 06:45.040
The novel is Midnight at the Well of Souls.

06:45.360 --> 06:46.540
The author is Jack Chalker.

06:46.720 --> 06:48.460
The book concerns the well world,

06:48.740 --> 06:51.640
an artificial planet constructed by a vanished civilization.

06:51.920 --> 06:55.840
The well world is divided into 1,560 separate environments.

06:56.260 --> 06:57.360
Separate worlds, really.

06:57.360 --> 07:00.860
Each with its own climate, geography, and intelligent inhabitants.

07:01.180 --> 07:03.140
Each division is shaped like a hexagon,

07:03.300 --> 07:05.220
and for that reason they're called hexes.

07:06.000 --> 07:08.380
Chalker was in an isolated village called Stehekin,

07:08.580 --> 07:11.060
on the shore of Lake Chelan in central Washington state,

07:11.300 --> 07:12.880
when he got the idea for the well world.

07:14.420 --> 07:18.740
I got to sitting by the lake that night and talking with some people,

07:19.640 --> 07:29.680
and I got the idea for this large world built by a long dead race and so on,

07:29.700 --> 07:32.400
and I didn't really have much of an idea of what it was.

07:33.120 --> 07:38.140
And they do have a service out of Stehekin that'll take you up to Trailhead.

07:39.220 --> 07:42.720
And so I went up to Trailhead, and I wound up walking down.

07:42.920 --> 07:46.060
I'm a great hiker as long as the direction's down.

07:48.000 --> 07:50.340
I'm afraid I've never been to the bottom of the Grand Canyon

07:50.340 --> 07:52.640
because I can get down there, but I can't get back up.

07:53.340 --> 07:56.140
But here was a trail that was tailor-made for me.

07:56.260 --> 07:59.840
It was down the Cascades all the way.

08:01.100 --> 08:08.440
So I took it, and it took about eight and a half hours to walk the whole distance.

08:11.140 --> 08:14.140
And during that time, you go through eight climate zones.

08:14.500 --> 08:15.940
You start off in the snow.

08:16.760 --> 08:18.240
You wind up in a rainforest.

08:19.720 --> 08:22.120
And some of the changes are rather abrupt.

08:22.120 --> 08:23.600
You just go around a switchback,

08:24.160 --> 08:27.300
and it just changes from one climate to another,

08:27.440 --> 08:32.800
each with its own different plants and insects and occasional mammals.

08:33.600 --> 08:35.320
Even the birds seem to be different.

08:35.560 --> 08:38.100
And I thought, yeah, this is how that big world would be like.

08:39.180 --> 08:43.740
So even while I was on my way down, I was kind of scribbling ideas.

08:45.920 --> 08:50.960
And I got the idea for this giant world composed of basically worldlets,

08:52.280 --> 08:57.500
different abrupt geography, climate, landforms, you name it,

08:57.880 --> 08:59.560
each with its own dominant race.

09:02.380 --> 09:05.380
By the time I hit bottom, I had it pretty well worked out,

09:05.400 --> 09:09.340
although I didn't really know what the shape of the things were going to be.

09:10.740 --> 09:11.840
Back home in Maryland,

09:11.840 --> 09:14.000
he got some help on the shape of the well world.

09:15.340 --> 09:19.620
I was discussing the idea with a science fiction fan named Ben Yalow,

09:19.940 --> 09:23.780
the son of the Nobel winner, Rosalind Yalow.

09:24.240 --> 09:25.800
And he says,

09:25.980 --> 09:27.880
why don't you just use an Avalon Hill game board?

09:29.460 --> 09:31.260
And I thought, yeah, that would work.

09:31.620 --> 09:34.180
So we got out an Avalon Hill map,

09:35.360 --> 09:36.700
a war game map,

09:36.740 --> 09:39.020
and a little trusty calculator.

09:39.020 --> 09:45.600
We laid a grid of these hexagons around a roughly Earth-sized world.

09:46.220 --> 09:48.820
Of course, we cannot cover a sphere with hexagons.

09:49.060 --> 09:52.400
So that means we had the north zone and the south zone,

09:52.640 --> 09:55.800
which would be the embassy's entry and exit points.

09:56.860 --> 09:58.360
That would cover our sphere.

09:59.140 --> 10:01.960
And then it was just simply a matter of sitting down,

10:02.080 --> 10:05.120
listing what was required to do,

10:05.400 --> 10:10.360
what kind of creatures and land climate and so on

10:10.360 --> 10:12.640
I would have to do for the route of the story.

10:13.560 --> 10:15.140
Dropping by Avalon Hill,

10:15.320 --> 10:17.100
which I lived very near at the time,

10:17.660 --> 10:19.080
picking up some blank maps,

10:20.180 --> 10:22.000
and just working it out from there.

10:23.400 --> 10:24.840
What Chalker worked out

10:24.840 --> 10:26.400
turned into his best-known novel,

10:26.820 --> 10:27.960
Midnight at the Well of Souls.

10:28.220 --> 10:30.460
It was so popular that it went out of print

10:30.460 --> 10:32.420
a few months after its initial press run.

10:32.580 --> 10:34.740
And Chalker has added four novels since then,

10:35.080 --> 10:36.820
making a five-book series in the well world.

10:37.060 --> 10:40.040
The whole thing turned out to be a colorful and exciting epic

10:40.040 --> 10:41.420
on the origin of the universe

10:41.420 --> 10:42.940
and all of the creatures in it.

10:43.100 --> 10:45.700
It should fascinate any reader of science fiction.

10:46.020 --> 10:47.720
More on Jack Chalker next time.

