12:10.340 --> 12:15.680
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:18.400 --> 12:20.040
And here are your hosts.

12:24.780 --> 12:27.180
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews.

12:27.460 --> 12:32.020
The five novels in Jack Chalker's Well World series are based on a familiar science fiction concept.

12:32.020 --> 12:38.300
And that concept is the notion of a long-dead race of superior beings whose artifacts are found by humans.

12:38.520 --> 12:42.520
But there are a couple of interesting twists given to this concept by Chalker.

12:42.920 --> 12:46.020
One twist is the principal artifact by the vanished race.

12:46.160 --> 12:48.320
It's a planet called the Well World.

12:48.700 --> 12:54.760
It's artificial, and its interior is a supercomputer that can transform matter into all sorts of living creatures.

12:55.040 --> 12:58.840
It's really a laboratory planet where species are created and tested

12:58.840 --> 13:01.840
before being transferred to various places throughout the universe.

13:02.420 --> 13:07.480
And the other twist is that these superior beings, called the Markovians, aren't actually gone.

13:07.800 --> 13:10.940
They just transform themselves into other, more primitive beings.

13:11.480 --> 13:13.280
Chalker talks about the Markovians.

13:14.020 --> 13:23.340
They got to the point where they were gone, literally, where their devices could conjure up anything they wanted, just with a mere thought of it.

13:25.320 --> 13:31.880
I sense that it pointed out to me that they're sort of like the Krell in the old movie Forbidden Planet,

13:31.880 --> 13:34.840
and that they reached this godhead status.

13:35.460 --> 13:41.220
But the Krell experiment failed because they couldn't control their passions.

13:41.620 --> 13:45.720
And the Markovian experiment succeeded, and they literally became gods.

13:46.140 --> 13:47.440
Then they became miserable.

13:48.020 --> 13:49.940
There was nothing left to attain.

13:50.300 --> 13:51.820
There was nothing left to know.

13:51.820 --> 13:52.760
There was nothing left.

13:52.960 --> 13:59.680
You know, you got a bunch of creatures that spent millions of years rising to this point,

13:59.760 --> 14:01.520
and they sit around and they say, is this all there is?

14:02.900 --> 14:05.960
At this point, the Markovians decided to start all over again.

14:06.840 --> 14:13.180
The idea of the great experiment came about was to redo it,

14:13.600 --> 14:19.780
to literally start the Markovians over from scratch with different kinds of creatures,

14:20.100 --> 14:25.520
different environments, with no real value system.

14:25.740 --> 14:28.080
I mean, they have to develop their own unique value system.

14:28.440 --> 14:29.360
They do.

14:30.220 --> 14:36.780
And as a result, they're grown and they're tested on this laboratory world, the well world.

14:37.120 --> 14:42.060
And then they were the ones that worked, the ones that showed promise of survival,

14:42.060 --> 14:48.320
were then set into motion out throughout the universe, including man.

14:50.940 --> 14:59.640
And they had the hopes that eventually one of these races would reach a state of perfection

15:00.820 --> 15:03.580
that would not be empty or hollow.

15:04.320 --> 15:10.620
Now, I personally believe that when you reach that state, it is empty and hollow.

15:11.400 --> 15:17.140
But that's just my feeling.

15:17.380 --> 15:19.860
Other people might certainly do think differently.

15:21.400 --> 15:26.780
The Markovians create hundreds of different species, all intelligent, but all incredibly different.

15:27.040 --> 15:30.760
We asked Chalker how he gets ideas for creating such a variety of aliens.

15:32.300 --> 15:34.180
I used a variety of things.

15:34.360 --> 15:38.140
In some cases, a good pictorial natural history text

15:38.140 --> 15:40.980
will give you more weird creatures than you've ever seen,

15:42.600 --> 15:44.060
which can be modified.

15:45.840 --> 15:47.360
Some came out of mythology.

15:49.640 --> 15:52.120
Some came more or less direct out of fantasia.

15:53.140 --> 15:54.380
Sources like that.

15:55.360 --> 15:59.620
And a few came out of comic book concepts.

16:00.800 --> 16:04.160
You know, you just draw them in from all over

16:04.160 --> 16:06.360
and you use basic shapes and basic types.

16:06.360 --> 16:12.000
And then you adjust them to what would happen if these were real,

16:12.140 --> 16:14.780
fantasia, intelligent, you know, creatures.

16:16.300 --> 16:23.100
I found very, very little trouble in coming up with an enormous variety of them.

16:23.620 --> 16:26.200
I'm not sure whether I could come up with 1,560,

16:26.200 --> 16:29.680
which is the number I would have to to visit every hex in the well world.

16:30.140 --> 16:33.240
But I've had no trouble coming up with the 200 or 300 so far.

16:33.980 --> 16:35.920
More with Jack Chalker next time.

