18:22.400 --> 18:27.000
Before he became a best-selling science fiction author, Jack Chalker was an avid fan who built

18:27.000 --> 18:29.600
an amateur fanzine into a science fiction publishing company.

18:29.960 --> 18:34.800
Chalker started the fanzine in his early teens as a way of making contacts in the field of science fiction

18:34.800 --> 18:37.540
and with the possibility of making a little money at it.

18:38.960 --> 18:40.940
That basically was the reason.

18:41.160 --> 18:48.260
We started with a fanzine which was run off actually at a school at the beginning because we didn't have anything else.

18:50.460 --> 18:55.920
And he'd got some reasonably good reactions, so I started building up from there.

18:55.920 --> 19:06.500
While I was doing that, actually, I had correspondence already with enormous numbers of people, both professional and fan.

19:07.320 --> 19:14.100
I had so much correspondence, I can't believe how many people I was contacting on a regular basis.

19:14.100 --> 19:19.760
And so I started tapping them and created the fanzine Mirage.

19:20.420 --> 19:29.920
The addition of a $40 surplus mimeograph found in an old store, which I still own, by the way, which still works,

19:31.800 --> 19:35.560
I was able to start putting out a fanzine called Mirage.

19:36.720 --> 19:42.760
The fanzine was successful because of its high quality, and it led into a small publishing company, Mirage Press.

19:44.360 --> 19:50.540
I was serious and constructive at the same time that everybody else was being just sort of kid hobbyist.

19:51.060 --> 19:58.680
I really had a magazine that discussed the literature, discussed the writers and so on, past and present,

19:58.900 --> 20:01.580
at a time when very few of these were coming out.

20:01.940 --> 20:08.420
And so I attracted a rather large audience of collectors and professional writers and artists and so on.

20:08.420 --> 20:18.500
And I was able to create out of that the Mirage Press, which started off again as mimeographed publications

20:18.500 --> 20:27.060
and then later grew as capital grew into a hardcover and quality paperback publishing account.

20:29.100 --> 20:32.480
Chalker says that Mirage Press was successful from the start.

20:33.680 --> 20:38.020
I started off with a bibliography of H.P. Lovecraft, which I did myself.

20:38.840 --> 20:44.140
Put it together, mimeographed it with the help of August Derleth,

20:45.680 --> 20:49.800
who owned the rights to the H.P. Lovecraft material at the time.

20:49.800 --> 21:00.220
And sold it for what in 1960 was a horrendous fee of $1.

21:01.420 --> 21:03.040
And we sold 100 of them.

21:04.700 --> 21:09.860
Mirage Press publishes nonfiction materials such as bibliographies and critical studies of authors.

21:10.640 --> 21:13.020
Chalker leaves the publishing of fiction to the large companies.

21:14.100 --> 21:20.440
You can't compete with Doubleday, Simon & Schuster and so on for the good stuff in fiction.

21:20.960 --> 21:24.320
And although I did do a little bit of fiction,

21:26.040 --> 21:32.440
getting into print some books of work that I thought was very, very neglected,

21:33.300 --> 21:35.160
you really have to promote fiction.

21:36.480 --> 21:39.860
Whereas nonfiction and reference material is always,

21:41.020 --> 21:44.020
there's always a heavy market and there's been a growing market for it.

21:44.600 --> 21:46.800
And so I concentrated in that end.

21:47.580 --> 21:50.720
And we came up with some rather successful books,

21:50.820 --> 21:53.940
Guide to Middle Earth, which in its Ballantine form,

21:54.100 --> 21:57.440
which I still own a piece of, is still selling well,

21:57.600 --> 21:58.500
an atlas of fantasy.

22:01.720 --> 22:05.080
Obviously, we did three books on sword and sorcery fiction

22:05.080 --> 22:06.940
before the comic books discovered Conan.

22:08.800 --> 22:12.760
And occasionally we did rather odd materials,

22:12.900 --> 22:18.900
such as a collection of all of the Ferdinand Feghoot bad puns

22:19.580 --> 22:22.360
that have been published over the years, this kind of thing.

22:23.400 --> 22:27.020
Mostly, though, we were serious reference works,

22:27.020 --> 22:28.700
and we still have a number of them that are standard.

